of, he's going
to go try and run the world.

28:50.162 --> 28:53.999 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Jamil Jaffer
worked with Gorsuch
at the law firm and later as his
law clerk

28:54.032 --> 28:55.867 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and has remained a friend.

28:55.901 --> 29:01.139 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Jaffer now teaches at the
Antonin Scalia Law
School at George Mason
University, named for

29:01.173 --> 29:03.008 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the man who Neil Gorsuch may
replace.

29:03.041 --> 29:07.179 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JAMIL JAFFER: One of the
interesting things
about Judge Gorsuch is that he
really is a

29:07.212 --> 29:08.180 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
judge's judge.

29:08.213 --> 29:09.514 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What does that
mean, exactly?

29:09.548 --> 29:11.049 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAMIL JAFFER: So he's not
looking to get a
particular outcome.

29:11.083 --> 29:14.186 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He doesn't have a particular
policy view that
he wants to impose upon the law.

29:14.219 --> 29:18.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What it is, is it's applying the
laws Congress
wrote, applying the Constitution
as the people

29:18.790 --> 29:22.394 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who wrote it understood it,
right, and not
sort of going outside of those
bounds.

29:22.427 --> 29:28.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And so maybe that's a
conservative philosophy,
in the sense that it's
originalist, it's textualist,

29:28.066 --> 29:32.070 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the mold of, I would say,
Justice Scalia,
but also very mainstream, in the
sense that

29:32.104 --> 29:35.774 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
when you apply it to any given
case, you're
not going to necessarily like
all the outcomes.

29:35.807 --> 29:40.178 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: OK, I understand
it, but it
also sounds a little maybe naive
in the political

29:40.212 --> 29:41.613 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
context we're talking about,
right?

29:41.647 --> 29:43.515 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JAMIL JAFFER: Sure.

29:43.548 --> 29:47.219 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Scalia was a
lightning rod
on all kinds of social and all
kinds of political

29:47.252 --> 29:48.220 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
issues.

29:48.253 --> 29:49.221 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JAMIL JAFFER: Don't get me
wrong.

29:49.254 --> 29:50.489 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I mean, Judge Gorsuch is
certainly conservative.

29:50.522 --> 29:52.491 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I would say he's in the
mainstream of
conservatism.

29:52.524 --> 29:56.094 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You're not going to get a
liberal judge from
President Donald Trump, right?

29:56.128 --> 29:57.963 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's not what he ran on.

29:57.996 --> 30:00.699 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But if you're looking for sort
of a mainstream
conservative, a judge's judge,
somebody who's

30:00.732 --> 30:04.636 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
not going to go out of the way
to either get
to a conservative outcome or a
liberal outcome,

30:04.670 --> 30:06.138 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
then you have got Neil Gorsuch.

30:06.171 --> 30:09.374 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What is known of
Neil Gorsuch's
views?

30:09.408 --> 30:14.546 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Among his early writings, a book
on assisted
suicide, arguing against the
practice and

30:14.579 --> 30:20.052 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for the inviolability of human
life, and a
"National Review" article, from
before he

30:20.085 --> 30:25.323 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
became a judge, critical of
liberals who -- quote
-- "have become addicted to the
courtroom,

30:25.357 --> 30:29.928 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
rather than elected leaders and
the ballot
box, as the primary means of
effecting their

30:29.961 --> 30:31.763 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
social agenda."

30:31.797 --> 30:37.169 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In a prominent and contentious
case, Judge
Gorsuch sided with Hobby Lobby
stores, which

30:37.202 --> 30:43.508 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
objected to a requirement under
the Affordable
Care Act that it provide
contraception coverage.

30:43.542 --> 30:46.645 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That decision was later upheld
by the Supreme
Court.

30:46.678 --> 30:51.183 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But he's also written on the
needs of low-income
litigants and prisoners, calling
for more

30:51.216 --> 30:57.723 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
affordable legal services and
better representation
in death penalty cases.

30:57.756 --> 30:59.791 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Gorsuch was personally close to
Justice Scalia.

30:59.825 --> 31:05.430 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In a speech last year at Case
Western Reserve,
he spoke of being on the ski
slope when he

31:05.464 --> 31:06.798 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
learned of Scalia's death.

31:06.832 --> 31:09.634 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NEIL GORSUCH: I immediately lost
what breath
I had left.

31:09.668 --> 31:14.539 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I'm not embarrassed to admit
that I couldn't
see the rest of the way down the
mountain

31:14.573 --> 31:15.907 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
through the tears.

31:15.941 --> 31:18.243 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: He added this of
their shared
judicial philosophy.

31:18.276 --> 31:22.114 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NEIL GORSUCH: As Justice Scalia
put it -- and
it rings true to me -- if you're
going to

31:22.147 --> 31:25.617 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
be a good and faithful judge,
you have to
resign yourself to the fact that
you're not

31:25.650 --> 31:28.487 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
always going to like the
conclusions you reach.

31:28.520 --> 31:32.524 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you like them all the time,
you're probably
doing something wrong.

31:32.557 --> 31:37.896 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NARRATOR: Neil Gorsuch is a
family man, a
conservative from Colorado.

31:37.929 --> 31:41.299 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Conservatives and
business
groups like what they see.

31:41.333 --> 31:45.137 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NARRATOR: Why did he make it
harder to hold
Wall Street accountable or for
women to get

31:45.170 --> 31:46.972 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
birth control?

31:47.005 --> 31:50.308 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But liberals see
a different
picture, one in which Gorsuch
could fall on

31:50.342 --> 31:53.078 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the court's far right end of the
spectrum.

31:53.111 --> 31:54.412 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELIZABETH WYDRA, Constitutional
Accountability
Center: You know, it really
doesn't matter

31:54.446 --> 31:59.017 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
whether he's a genial person or
a great guy
to go skiing with.

31:59.050 --> 32:00.919 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I'm sure all of those things are
true.

32:00.952 --> 32:05.690 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But what really matters is his
record and
whether he can be the
independent justice

32:05.724 --> 32:09.594 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that we really need on the
Supreme Court to
provide a check against
potential overreach

32:09.628 --> 32:11.429 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
from the elective branches.

32:11.463 --> 32:15.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Elizabeth Wydra,
head of the
Constitutional Accountability
Center, a public

32:15.734 --> 32:21.640 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
interest law and advocacy group,
says Donald
Trump set out a clear litmus
test, including

32:21.673 --> 32:24.810 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a willingness to overturn Roe v.
Wade.

32:24.843 --> 32:28.013 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One can only assume, she told
me, Gorsuch
met the test.

32:28.046 --> 32:32.951 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELIZABETH WYDRA: Certainly, we
want our justices
to look to the text and history
of the Constitution,

32:32.984 --> 32:37.222 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but what I'm concerned about is
whether he
looks to the text and history of
the whole

32:37.255 --> 32:42.828 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Constitution, including
amendments that made
our Constitution more equal,
ensuring that

32:42.861 --> 32:46.965 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
people of all colors, men and
women are treated
equally as citizens.

32:46.998 --> 32:51.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: It almost sounds
as though
anybody that Trump would put
forward, because

32:51.570 --> 32:53.171 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
he was very clear about what he
wanted, right?

32:53.205 --> 32:56.441 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ELIZABETH WYDRA: I think this is
where the
hearing becomes very important.

32:56.474 --> 33:02.514 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is a big burden placed on
Neil Gorsuch
to come before the Senate
Judiciary Committee

33:02.547 --> 33:08.186 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and show that, despite the
process by which
he was picked, replete with
litmus tests and

33:08.220 --> 33:12.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
high rhetoric from Donald Trump,
Neil Gorsuch
has the burden to show the
Senate Judiciary

33:12.891 --> 33:17.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Committee that he will be this
fair, independent
judge who will follow the law
where it leads.

33:17.562 --> 33:21.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Neil Gorsuch has
spent recent
weeks meeting with senators on
both sides

33:21.733 --> 33:27.939 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the aisle and preparing for
those hearings,
a very public debate now under
way.

33:27.973 --> 33:30.575 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
From Washington, I'm Jeffrey
Brown for the
"PBS NewsHour."

33:30.609 --> 33:35.747 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And we continue
our look at
the potential next Supreme Court
justice,

33:35.780 --> 33:41.152 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Neil Gorsuch, and the opening
day of his confirmation
hearings with "NewsHour" regular
Marcia Coyle

33:41.186 --> 33:43.188 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of "The National Law Journal."

33:43.221 --> 33:47.359 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Tom Goldstein, he's founder of
SCOTUSblog.com.

33:47.392 --> 33:52.330 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Pam Karlan, she's a professor of
law at Stanford
University who worked in the
Justice Department

33:52.364 --> 33:57.302 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
during the Obama administration,
and Paul
Clement, a former solicitor
general under

33:57.335 --> 33:59.137 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
President George W. Bush.

33:59.170 --> 34:01.306 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we welcome all of you to the
"NewsHour."

34:01.339 --> 34:04.309 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Marcia, I'm going to start with
you.

34:04.342 --> 34:06.077 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Overall takeaway from today's
session?

34:06.111 --> 34:09.714 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE, "The National Law
Journal":
Well, the first day usually is
not all that

34:09.748 --> 34:11.783 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
substantive.

34:11.816 --> 34:15.353 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The hearing played out the way
it has traditionally.

34:15.387 --> 34:19.224 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The senators -- each senator has
an opening
statement.

34:19.257 --> 34:23.995 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Then there is an introduction of
the nominee,
and the nominee's opening
statement.

34:24.029 --> 34:25.797 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
That did happen.

34:25.830 --> 34:33.305 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But what we gather from the
first day is,
we see where the concerns are on
both sides,

34:33.338 --> 34:40.545 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
where the questioning may lead,
what kind
of difficulties the nominee may
have in answering

34:40.578 --> 34:42.380 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
some of the questions.

34:42.414 --> 34:49.354 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On the Republican said today, we
saw a lot
of emphasis on Judge Gorsuch's
qualifications.

34:49.387 --> 34:56.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On the Democratic side, we saw
specific concerns
about opinions he has written in
areas, certain

34:56.461 --> 35:04.970 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
areas such as workers'
protection, whether
he would give deference to
agencies' rules.

35:05.003 --> 35:08.473 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, it's really a laying out of
what's to
come.

35:08.506 --> 35:10.909 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Paul Clement,
what was your
main takeaway today?

35:10.942 --> 35:14.012 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL CLEMENT, Former U.S.
Solicitor General:
Well, I thought probably the
single most interesting

35:14.045 --> 35:17.082 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
part of the hearing was Judge
Gorsuch's own
statement.

35:17.115 --> 35:23.188 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think what the American
public saw was
somebody who's very poised, very
experienced

35:23.221 --> 35:28.393 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- he's been a federal court of
appeals judge
for over 10 years -- and I think
somebody

35:28.426 --> 35:35.433 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by kind of any conventional
standard is qualified
to be on the Supreme Court of
the United States.

35:35.467 --> 35:37.902 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And so I think that will
probably give us
an indication.

35:37.936 --> 35:43.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We will obviously see a lot more
of Judge
Gorsuch in tomorrow's hearings
answering questions

35:43.475 --> 35:46.177 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the back and forth, but that
was really
the highlight for me.

35:46.211 --> 35:50.949 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Pam Karlan,
again, we
only heard just a moment or so
from Judge

35:50.982 --> 35:54.419 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Gorsuch himself today, but what
was your main
takeaway in terms of what we now
know?

35:54.452 --> 35:58.823 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAM KARLAN, Stanford Law School:
Well, from
Judge Gorsuch himself, he made
this point

35:58.857 --> 36:05.530 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- and you saw it in the clip --
that in 97
percent of his cases below, the
decision is

36:05.563 --> 36:06.931 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
unanimous.

36:06.965 --> 36:09.467 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's totally different from
what happens
on the Supreme Court.

36:09.501 --> 36:14.839 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The job of a judge and the job
of a justice
are very different, because
justices are resolving

36:14.873 --> 36:17.442 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the constitutional questions
that divide us
most.

36:17.475 --> 36:21.446 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think you got a sense from
the senators
that the senators, too,
recognize that there

36:21.479 --> 36:24.049 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
are two very different
constitutional visions
at stake here.

36:24.082 --> 36:30.388 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, and I
wanted to ask you
about that, Paul -- Tom
Goldstein, because

36:30.422 --> 36:32.991 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it struck me, he said, that's
how we do it
in the West.

36:33.024 --> 36:39.164 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He said 97 percent of his -- of
the cases
he decided on were unanimous.

36:39.197 --> 36:42.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Even more were decided by -- he
was in the
majority.

36:42.734 --> 36:45.070 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Does that tell us something
about him or not?

36:45.103 --> 36:47.539 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
TOM GOLDSTEIN, Founder,
SCOTUSblog.com: It
probably doesn't tell us as much
about the

36:47.572 --> 36:49.974 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
outcomes in the cases, in the
cases where
there was a division.

36:50.008 --> 36:53.912 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When you get to the Supreme
Court, the stakes
are harder and the -- higher,
and the questions

36:53.945 --> 36:55.680 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
are harder.

36:55.713 --> 36:59.551 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't think that there is any
suggestion
that you would really see Neil
Gorsuch kind

36:59.584 --> 37:03.221 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of assuming the mantle of the
center of justice
on the Supreme Court.

37:03.254 --> 37:06.958 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Rather, he's going to fit the
mold of the
person that he's replacing,
Justice Scalia.

37:06.991 --> 37:09.494 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In all likelihood, he's going to
be a solidly
conservative judge.

37:09.527 --> 37:14.232 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And what did you
hear today,
Marcia, in terms of lines that
you expect

37:14.265 --> 37:18.436 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the Democrats -- questioning,
criticism that
you expect the Democrats to...

37:18.470 --> 37:22.740 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: Judy, I think
every confirmation
hearing, at least ones that I
have covered,

37:22.774 --> 37:27.545 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
has something unique about it
that drives
the questioning.

37:27.579 --> 37:33.351 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And on the Democratic side today
and what
I think will drive a lot of the
questioning

37:33.384 --> 37:37.755 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is something that Senator
Klobuchar said that
sort of stayed with me.

37:37.789 --> 37:44.496 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She said, basically, we can't
evaluate your
credentials in a legal cocoon.

37:44.529 --> 37:48.967 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have to be evaluated in the
context of
the era that we live in.

37:49.000 --> 37:54.105 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And for her and her colleagues,
that context
is pretty much what they believe
the Trump

37:54.139 --> 37:56.307 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
administration has created.

37:56.341 --> 38:07.318 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She talked about the president's
criticisms
of judges, the obstacles to
voting, just a

38:07.352 --> 38:14.893 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
whole range of things that she
feels he has
to be measured against in terms
of his independence.

38:14.926 --> 38:22.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I think we're going to see a
lot of questioning
that follows along those lines.

38:22.467 --> 38:28.806 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of the sort of unfortunate
things, I think,
of what the Senate did on the
Garland nomination

38:28.840 --> 38:34.179 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was that it pushed the Supreme
Court into
a very bitter election campaign.

38:34.212 --> 38:40.385 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that resulted in both
candidates having
litmus tests for their judicial
nominees.

38:40.418 --> 38:42.153 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Right.

38:42.187 --> 38:44.756 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: And the fact that
President
Trump said that he would appoint
someone who,

38:44.789 --> 38:50.628 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for example, would overturn Roe
