48:56.700 --> 48:58.669 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
is never permanent.

48:58.702 --> 48:59.970 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We're constantly moving.

49:00.004 --> 49:01.438 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's constantly shifting.

49:01.472 --> 49:05.342 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I'm an American-born child to
Mexican immigrants.

49:05.376 --> 49:07.778 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, I'm at once Mexican and
American.

49:07.812 --> 49:09.613 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I'm in between.

49:09.647 --> 49:15.152 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That in-between space, that
in-between place
that I occupy is something that
is constantly

49:15.186 --> 49:16.954 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
changing within myself.

49:16.987 --> 49:23.561 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Dmitri
Obergfell's installation
reflects an internal identity
struggle.

49:23.594 --> 49:28.365 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He was raised in Colorado by his
American
mother and was estranged from
his Mexican

49:28.399 --> 49:30.935 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
father until recently.

49:30.968 --> 49:36.941 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For the museum, he recreated a
market typical
of many Latino neighborhoods in
Denver, one

49:36.974 --> 49:42.980 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that sells T-shirts, sculptures
of narco-saints
and praying hands with manicured
nails.

49:43.013 --> 49:47.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DMITRI OBERGFELL, Artist: The
reason I wanted
to explore this sort of theme in
this way

49:47.451 --> 49:52.723 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
using, like, this market is
because I have
kind of always existed on the
perimeter of

49:52.756 --> 49:54.058 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Latino culture.

49:54.091 --> 49:55.993 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: You feel
complicated when it
comes to identity?

49:56.026 --> 50:01.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DMITRI OBERGFELL: I think that
it would be
maybe in bad taste for me to
take this opportunity

50:01.999 --> 50:05.636 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and come into this exhibition
and say, OK,
I'm fully Latino now.

50:05.669 --> 50:10.474 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Like, for me, it was just about
exploring
and having this sort of
cathartic process

50:10.507 --> 50:13.310 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
to work through these
complicated identity
ideas.

50:13.344 --> 50:18.916 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Jaime Carrejo is
a professor
at Rocky Mountain College of Art
and a fourth-generation

50:18.949 --> 50:23.420 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
American who grew up in the
border city of
El Paso, Texas.

50:23.454 --> 50:29.260 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He created his own border wall
with video
images of Mexico projected on
one side and

50:29.293 --> 50:31.128 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of the U.S. on the other.

50:31.161 --> 50:32.897 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAIME CARREJO, Professor, Rocky
Mountain College
of Art: I'm really interested in
the construction

50:32.930 --> 50:39.169 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of divisiveness and how we use
that to make
people part of a group or
exclude them.

50:39.203 --> 50:47.177 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In making art, you can create
complex discussions
about complex issues, because
things don't

50:47.211 --> 50:48.712 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
exist in dualities.

50:48.746 --> 50:50.681 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: That's
interesting, because
there is a duality here, right?

50:50.714 --> 50:52.449 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There's one country, and there's
another.

50:52.483 --> 50:55.386 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAIME CARREJO: You have the
dualities, but
the wall itself, because of the
reflective

50:55.419 --> 50:57.755 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
materials, they end up
collapsing on each
other.

50:57.788 --> 51:02.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There would be moments where the
image of
Mexico will be transcribed on
the image of

51:02.593 --> 51:03.594 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the United States.

51:03.627 --> 51:05.262 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You have this whole different
landscape.

51:05.296 --> 51:10.734 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, you end up with this complex
layering
and mix of an image, which I
think is the

51:10.768 --> 51:13.737 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
perfect metaphor of what it
means to be a
U.S. citizen of the United
States.

51:13.771 --> 51:20.244 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Landscape and two
worlds colliding
was also the focus for Daniela
Edburg, who's

51:20.277 --> 51:23.013 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
lived her life back and forth in
both countries.

51:23.047 --> 51:29.753 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Her piece, titled Uprooted,
